sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M45178
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: (For class project) A composite device that employs the LexA/RecA system as an ionizing radiation biosensor, triggering luminescence response from Metridia longa luciferase and odor response from lysine decarboxylase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Jay Barlow
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Composite of synthetic analogs, eukaryotic and prokaryotic promoters, and eukaryotic coding sequences.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M45172
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Lysine decarboxylase consumes protons to metabolize L-lysine to cadaverine and CO2. Expression of the cadA gene is normally controlled by cadC. Lysine decarboxylase uses pyridoxal 5'-phosphate as a cofactor. This is a HYPOTHETICAL part that has not gone under any testing but has been changed to biobrick format.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Andrew Alarcon Parker
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: From E.coli (K12)cds. Sequence originally published by Meng,S.Y. and Bennett,G.N. in "Nucleotide sequence of the Escherichia coli cad operon: a system for neutralization of low extracellular pH" (1992)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Sequence has strangely enough been optimized for expression within the Felix cattus genome. It is suggested that it be optimized again for the desired clone species. Prefix and suffix RE sites have been removed from the sequence. Again this part has not been tested and is HYPOTHETICAL only.
